---
import ChapterEntry from '../components/blocks/ChapterEntry.astro';
import Prose from '../components/blocks/Prose.astro';
import DataTable from '../components/blocks/DataTable.astro';
import Diagram from '../components/blocks/Diagram.astro';
import type { Chapter } from '../data/chapters';

type Props = Chapter;
const { number, title } = Astro.props;
---

<ChapterEntry
  chapterNumber={number}
  title={title}
  lead="A session is a container."
/>

<Prose>
  <p>
    A session is the container around one running instance of the system. In
    the CLI, a session is a conversation. In a pipeline runner, a session is a
    single batch execution. In the kernel, a session is just an ID and a
    lifecycle.
  </p>
</Prose>

<Prose>
  <h2>Create</h2>
  <p>
    Session created with configuration. The Coordinator and Module Loader are
    set up. Nothing has been loaded yet. The system knows what it needs, but
    hasn't started yet.
  </p>

  <h2>Initialize</h2>
  <p>
    The Module Loader loads modules in fixed order. If the Orchestrator or
    Context Manager fails to load, the session stops immediately. Everything
    else is optional. <strong>Required:</strong> Orchestrator and Context
    Manager must mount successfully during Initialize. If either fails, the
    session stops.
  </p>

  <h2>Execute</h2>
  <p>
    The session receives a message. It passes the message to the Orchestrator
    and gets a response back. This phase is repeatable — each call is one turn
    of conversation. Between turns, all state is maintained.
  </p>

  <h2>Cleanup</h2>
  <p>
    <code>session:end</code> fires first (hooks get a final chance). Then the
    Coordinator cleans up modules. Then the Loader cleans up. All of this runs
    in a <code>finally</code> block — it always runs, even after errors.
  </p>
</Prose>

<Diagram
  src="/diagrams/session-tree.svg"
  width="wide"
  alt="Parent-child session tree showing sessions as isolated containers linked only by parent_id"
  caption="Sessions are self-contained. The only link between parent and child is parent_id."
/>

<DataTable caption="Parent-Child Sessions: Expectations vs Reality">
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>What you might expect</th>
        <th>What Amplifier does</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Child inherits parent's context</td>
        <td>Set <code>parent_id</code>. That is the only link.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Shared modules, shared memory</td>
        <td>No shared modules, memory, or config.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Changes in parent affect child</td>
        <td>Each session is fully self-contained.</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
</DataTable>

<Prose>
  <p>
    The core provides a <code>parent_id</code> field that links one session to
    another. That is the extent of what the kernel does. How parent-child
    relationships are used — delegation, sub-agents, task decomposition — is
    decided by Foundation and applications built on top of it.
  </p>

  <p>
    This is deliberately minimal. Automatic inheritance creates hidden
    dependencies; changes to the parent's conversation would affect the child
    unpredictably. Explicit is better: pass what you need, share nothing by
    default. Each session is self-contained and predictable.
  </p>

  <h2>Cancellation</h2>

  <p>
    Cancellation is cooperative, not preemptive. The kernel cannot forcibly
    stop an Orchestrator in the middle of its work. Instead, it sets a flag
    with three states:
  </p>

  <ol>
    <li><strong>No cancellation requested</strong> — normal operation continues.</li>
    <li><strong>Graceful cancellation</strong> — finish what you're doing, then stop.</li>
    <li><strong>Immediate cancellation</strong> — stop as soon as possible.</li>
  </ol>

  <p>
    The Orchestrator must check this flag periodically. If it ignores the
    flag, cancellation doesn't happen.
  </p>

  <h2>Cleanup order</h2>

  <p>
    When a session ends, cleanup always runs. The <code>session:end</code>{' '}
    event fires first, giving hooks a final opportunity to act. Then the
    Coordinator cleans up modules in reverse load order. Then the Loader
    cleans up. This entire sequence is wrapped in a <code>finally</code>{' '}
    block — it runs even after errors, even after a crash.
  </p>

  <p>
    When you see session files on disk — <code>transcript.jsonl</code>,{' '}
    <code>events.jsonl</code>, <code>metadata.json</code> — the kernel didn't
    write them. Hook modules did. Remove every hook, and the session still
    runs identically. No trace on disk, but the conversation works the same.
  </p>
</Prose>
